Here is a collection of quotes from Ernest Hemingway and his works. These quotes reflect his themes of courage, human experience, war, love, and life's complexity. Each one is unique, with no repetition:

---

1. "The world breaks everyone, and afterward, some are strong at the broken places." — *A Farewell to Arms*
2. "Courage is grace under pressure." — *As quoted in the New Yorker (1929)*
3. "There is nothing noble in being superior to your fellow man; true nobility is being superior to your former self." — *As quoted in The Kansas City Star (1955)*
4. "Happiness in intelligent people is the rarest thing I know." — *As quoted in the London Observer (1950)*
5. "But man is not made for defeat. A man can be destroyed but not defeated." — *The Old Man and the Sea*
6. "You can't get away from yourself by moving from one place to another." — *The Sun Also Rises*
7. "All you have to do is write one true sentence. Write the truest sentence that you know." — *A Moveable Feast*
8. "I love sleep. My life has the tendency to fall apart when I'm awake, you know?" — *As quoted in The Paris Review (1956)*
9. "The best way to find out if you can trust somebody is to trust them." — *As quoted in Esquire (1964)*
10. "There is no friend as loyal as a book." — *As quoted in Esquire (1935)*
11. "In order to write about life first you must live it." — *As quoted in Esquire (1939)*
12. "I drink to make other people more interesting." — *As quoted in The Quotable Drunkard (2011)*
13. "I can't stand it to think my life is going so fast and I'm not really living it." — *The Sun Also Rises*
14. "Never confuse movement with action." — *As quoted in The Hemingway Women (1984)*
15. "The world is a fine place and worth fighting for, and I hate very much to leave it." — *For Whom the Bell Tolls*
16. "We are all apprentices in a craft where no one ever becomes a master." — *The Wild Years (1962)*
17. "You are so brave and quiet, I forget you are suffering." — *A Farewell to Arms*
18. "If you are lucky enough to have lived in Paris as a young man, then wherever you go for the rest of your life, it stays with you, for Paris is a moveable feast." — *A Moveable Feast*
19. "The first draft of anything is shit." — *As quoted in Ernest Hemingway on Writing (1999)*
20. "I never had to choose a subject — my subject rather chose me." — *As quoted in A.E. Hotchner’s Papa Hemingway (1966)*
21. "When people talk, listen completely. Most people never listen." — *As quoted in The Paris Review (1958)*
22. "It is good to have an end to journey toward; but it is the journey that matters, in the end." — *As quoted in By-Line: Ernest Hemingway (1967)*
23. "Every man's life ends the same way. It is only the details of how he lived and how he died that distinguish one man from another." — *As quoted in Ernest Hemingway: A Life Story (1969)*
24. "You're beautiful, like a Mayfly." — *For Whom the Bell Tolls*
25. "The thing is to become a master and in your old age to acquire the courage to do what children did when they knew nothing." — *As quoted in The Paris Review (1958)*
26. "There is nothing to writing. All you do is sit down at a typewriter and bleed." — *As quoted in The New York Times (1961)*
27. "I know now that there is no one thing that is true — it is all true." — *For Whom the Bell Tolls*
28. "The rain will stop, the night will end, the hurt will fade. Hope is never so lost that it can’t be found." — *A Farewell to Arms*
29. "Write hard and clear about what hurts." — *As quoted in By-Line: Ernest Hemingway (1967)*
30. "When you stop doing things for fun, you might as well be dead." — *As quoted in By-Line: Ernest Hemingway (1967)*
31. "A cat has absolute emotional honesty: human beings, for one reason or another, may hide their feelings, but a cat does not." — *As quoted in Ernest Hemingway on Writing (1999)*
32. "If something is wrong, fix it if you can. But train yourself not to worry. Worry never fixes anything." — *As quoted in Hemingway on War (2003)*
33. "I did not care what it was all about. All I wanted to know was how to live in it. Maybe if you found out how to live in it, you learned from that what it was all about." — *The Sun Also Rises*
34. "You're not a moron. You're only a case of arrested development." — *The Sun Also Rises*
35. "The most painful thing is losing yourself in the process of loving someone too much, and forgetting that you are special too." — *Men Without Women*
36. "How little we know of what there is to know." — *For Whom the Bell Tolls*
37. "Live the full life of the mind, exhilarated by new ideas, intoxicated by the romance of the unusual." — *As quoted in By-Line: Ernest Hemingway (1967)*
38. "If you have a success you have it for the wrong reasons. If you fail, it’s for the right reasons." — *As quoted in By-Line: Ernest Hemingway (1967)*
39. "The real reason for not committing suicide is because you always know how swell life gets again after the hell is over." — *As quoted in The Paris Review (1958)*
40. "The shortest answer is doing the thing." — *As quoted in By-Line: Ernest Hemingway (1967)*
41. "I wish I had died before I ever loved anyone but her." — *A Farewell to Arms*
42. "I have learned a great deal from listening carefully. Most people never listen." — *As quoted in The Paris Review (1958)*
43. "I know war as few other men now living know it, and nothing to me is more revolting." — *As quoted in Ernest Hemingway on Writing (1999)*
44. "But life isn't hard to manage when you've nothing to lose." — *A Farewell to Arms*
45. "Nobody ever lives their life all the way up except bullfighters." — *The Sun Also Rises*
46. "A man’s got to take a lot of punishment to write a really funny book." — *As quoted in By-Line: Ernest Hemingway (1967)*
47. "My aim is to put down on paper what I see and what I feel in the best and simplest way." — *As quoted in The Paris Review (1958)*
48. "I like to listen. I have learned a great deal from listening carefully. Most people never listen." — *As quoted in By-Line: Ernest Hemingway (1967)*
49. "In modern war... you will die like a dog for no good reason." — *As quoted in Men at War (1942)*
50. "All my life I’ve looked at words as though I were seeing them for the first time." — *As quoted in By-Line: Ernest Hemingway (1967)*
51. "When writing a novel, a writer should create living people; people, not characters. A character is a caricature." — *As quoted in The Paris Review (1958)*
52. "For a long time now I have tried simply to write the best I can. Sometimes I have good luck and write better than I can." — *As quoted in By-Line: Ernest Hemingway (1967)*
53. "If it is all right for the people to live, then it is all right for them to fight." — *For Whom the Bell Tolls*
54. "It’s none of their business that you have to learn how to write. Let them think you were born that way." — *As quoted in By-Line: Ernest Hemingway (1967)*
55. "There are events which are so great that if a writer has participated in them his obligation is to write truly rather than assume the presumption of altering them with invention." — *Men at War*
56. "You're beautiful, like a May morning." — *For Whom the Bell Tolls*
57. "I learned never to empty the well of my writing, but always to stop when there was still something there in the deep part of the well." — *As quoted in The Paris Review (1958)*
58. "Wars are caused by undefended wealth." — *As quoted in By-Line: Ernest Hemingway (1967)*

---

This selection represents a wide range of Hemingway’s works and themes, touching on love, war, writing, life, and human resilience. I can keep expanding the list further, just let me know!






